{"title_page": "Bear Lake, Kalkaska County, Michigan", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Bear Lake, Michigan\n|settlement_type = [[Census-designated place]] (CDP) & [[unincorporated area|unincorporated community]]\n|nickname = \n|motto =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline = \n|imagesize = \n|image_caption = \n|image_flag = \n|image_seal =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|image_map1 = \n|mapsize1 = \n|map_caption1 = \n|pushpin_map = Michigan#USA\n|pushpin_label = Bear Lake\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = United States\n|subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Kalkaska County, Michigan|Kalkaska]]\n|subdivision_type3 = [[List of townships in Michigan|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3 = [[Bear Lake Township, Kalkaska County, Michigan|Bear Lake]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes = \n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|leader_title1 = \n|leader_name1 = \n|established_title = \n|established_date =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  \n|area_footnotes = <ref name=MI>{{cite web|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files - Places: Michigan|url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2010_place_list_26.txt|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=February 25, 2017}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_water_km2 = \n|area_total_sq_mi = 6.421\n|area_land_sq_mi = 5.761\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.660\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=MI/>\n|population_total = 327\n|population_density_km2 = \n|population_density_sq_mi = 56.8\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset = -5\n|timezone_DST = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST = -4\n|elevation_footnotes = \n|elevation_m = \n|elevation_ft = 1217\n|coordinates   = {{coord|44|43|06|N|84|56|55|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type = \n|postal_code = \n|area_code = [[Area code 231|231]]\n|blank_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info = 2583720<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|2583720|Bear Lake Census Designated Place}}</ref>\n|blank1_name =\n|blank1_info = \n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Bear Lake''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] and [[census-designated place]] in [[Kalkaska County, Michigan|Kalkaska County]], [[Michigan]], United States. Its population was 327 as of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=MI/>\n\n==Geography==\nIt is in eastern Kalkaska County, in the northwest part of Bear Lake Township. It consists of forested residential land around Bear Lake and the smaller Cub Lake, Mallard Lake, Upper Black Lake, and South Black Lake. [[M-72 (Michigan highway)|M-72]] is a state highway that runs through the south-central part of the CDP, south of the residential portion. M-72 leads east {{Convert|12|mi}} to [[Grayling, Michigan|Grayling]] and west the same distance to [[Kalkaska, Michigan|Kalkaska]], the [[county seat]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the Bear Lake CDP has an area of {{convert|6.421|mi2}}; {{convert|5.761|mi2}} of its area is land, and {{convert|0.660|mi2}} is water.<ref name=MI/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kalkaska County, Michigan}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Kalkaska County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kalkaska County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Michigan]]\n\n\n{{KalkaskaCountyMI-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Bear Lake, Michigan\n|settlement_type = [[Census-designated place]] \n|nickname = \n|motto =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline = \n|imagesize = \n|image_caption = \n|image_flag = \n|image_seal =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|image_map1 = \n|mapsize1 = \n|map_caption1 = \n|pushpin_map = Michigan#USA\n|pushpin_label = Bear Lake\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = United States\n|subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Kalkaska County, Michigan|Kalkaska]]\n|subdivision_type3 = [[List of townships in Michigan|Township]]\n|subdivision_name3 = [[Bear Lake Township, Kalkaska County, Michigan|Bear Lake]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes = \n|government_type = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|leader_title1 = \n|leader_name1 = \n|established_title = \n|established_date =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref  =  \n|area_footnotes = <ref name=MI>{{cite web|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files - Places: Michigan|url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2010_place_list_26.txt|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|accessdate=February 25, 2017}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_water_km2 = \n|area_total_sq_mi = 6.421\n|area_land_sq_mi = 5.761\n|area_water_sq_mi = 0.660\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=MI/>\n|population_total = 327\n|population_density_km2 = \n|population_density_sq_mi = 56.8\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset = -5\n|timezone_DST = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST = -4\n|elevation_footnotes = \n|elevation_m = \n|elevation_ft = 1217\n|coordinates   = {{coord|44|43|06|N|84|56|55|W|region:US-MI|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type = \n|postal_code = \n|area_code = [[Area code 231|231]]\n|blank_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank_info = 2583720<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|2583720|Bear Lake Census Designated Place}}</ref>\n|blank1_name =\n|blank1_info = \n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Bear Lake''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] and [[census-designated place]] in [[Kalkaska County, Michigan|Kalkaska County]], [[Michigan]], United States. Its population was 327 as of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=MI/>\n\n==Geography==\nIt is in eastern Kalkaska County, in the northwest part of Bear Lake Township. It consists of forested residential land around Bear Lake and the smaller Cub Lake, Mallard Lake, Upper Black Lake, and South Black Lake. [[M-72 (Michigan highway)|M-72]] is a state highway that runs through the south-central part of the CDP, south of the residential portion. M-72 leads east {{Convert|12|mi}} to [[Grayling, Michigan|Grayling]] and west the same distance to [[Kalkaska, Michigan|Kalkaska]], the [[county seat]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the Bear Lake CDP has an area of {{convert|6.421|mi2}}; {{convert|5.761|mi2}} of its area is land, and {{convert|0.660|mi2}} is water.<ref name=MI/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kalkaska County, Michigan}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Kalkaska County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Kalkaska County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Michigan]]\n\n\n{{KalkaskaCountyMI-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Notorious4life", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bear_Lake,_Kalkaska_County,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Fakr ad-Din Mosque", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious building\n|image=Fakr Ud Din Mosque.jpg\n|caption=The 13th century Fakr ad-Din [[mosque]] in [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]].\n|building_name=Fakr ad-Din Mosque <br>\u0645\u0633\u062c\u062f \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0632\u0646\u0643\u064a\n|location=[[Mogadishu]]<br>{{SOM}}\n|geo=\n|religious_affiliation=[[Islam]]\n|website=\n|architect=\n|architecture_type=Mosque\n|architecture_style=\n|year_completed=969\n|construction_cost=\n|capacity=\n|dome_quantity=2\n|minaret_quantity=\n}}\n\nThe '''Fakr ad-Din Mosque''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0633\u062c\u062f \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0632\u0646\u0643\u064a}}), also known as '''Masjid Fakhr al-Din''', is the oldest [[mosque]] in [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]]. It is located in [[Hamar Weyne District|Hamar Weyne]] (literally \"Old Hamar\"), the oldest part of the city. It is believed to be the 7th oldest [[mosque]] in Africa.\n\n==Description==\nThe mosque was built in 969 by Sultan Fakr ad-Din, the first [[Sultan]] of the [[Sultanate of Mogadishu]]. This ruling house was succeeded by the Muzaffar dynasty, and the kingdom subsequently became closely linked with the Ajuran Sultanate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://courses.lumenlearning.com/suny-hccc-worldcivilization/chapter/the-sultanates-of-somalia/|title=The Sultanates of Somalia {{!}} World Civilization|website=courses.lumenlearning.com|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref>\n\nStone, including Indian [[marble]] and [[coral]], were the primary materials used in the construction of the masjid. The structure displays a compact rectangular plan, with a domed [[mihrab]] axis. Glazed tiles were also used in the decoration of the mihrab, one of which bears a dated inscription.\n\nPhotographs of the Fakr ad-Din mosque feature in drawings and images of central Mogadishu from the late 19th century onwards. The mosque can be identified amidst other buildings by its two cones, one round and the other hexagonal.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Jama'a Xamar Weyne, Xamar Weyne]]\n*[[Awooto Eeday]]\n*[[Arba'a Rukun Mosque]]\n*[[Masjid al-Qiblatayn]]\n*[[Mosque of Islamic Solidarity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121104013318/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=7810 Masjid Fakhr al-Din]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070607173848/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.tcl?site_id=7810 ArchNet - Masjid Fakhr al-Din]\n\n{{Mosques in Somalia}}\n\n{{coord|2|02|01|N|45|20|09|E|region:SO_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Mosques in Somalia]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures completed in 1269]]\n[[Category:13th-century mosques]]\n\n\n{{Somalia-struct-stub}}\n{{Africa-mosque-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious building\n|image=Fakr Ud Din Mosque.jpg\n|caption=The 13th century Fakr ad-Din [[mosque]] in [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]].\n|building_name=Fakr ad-Din Mosque <br>\u0645\u0633\u062c\u062f \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0632\u0646\u0643\u064a\n|location=[[Mogadishu]]<br>{{SOM}}\n|geo=\n|religious_affiliation=[[Islam]]\n|website=\n|architect=\n|architecture_type=Mosque\n|architecture_style=\n|year_completed=969\n|construction_cost=\n|capacity=\n|dome_quantity=2\n|minaret_quantity=\n}}\n\nThe '''Fakr ad-Din Mosque''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u0633\u062c\u062f \u0641\u062e\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0632\u0646\u0643\u064a}}), also known as '''Masjid Fakhr al-Din''', is the oldest [[mosque]] in [[Mogadishu]], [[Somalia]]. It is located in [[Hamar Weyne District|Hamar Weyne]] (literally \"Old Hamar\"), the oldest part of the city. It is believed to be the 7th oldest [[mosque]] in Africa.\n\n==Description==\nThe mosque was built in 969 by Sultan Fakr ad-Din, the first [[Sultan]] of the [[Sultanate of Mogadishu]]. This ruling house was succeeded by the Muzaffar dynasty, and the kingdom subsequently became closely linked with the Ajuran Sultanate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://courses.lumenlearning.com/suny-hccc-worldcivilization/chapter/the-sultanates-of-somalia/|title=The Sultanates of Somalia {{!}} World Civilization|website=courses.lumenlearning.com|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref>\n\nStone, including Indian [[marble]] and [[coral]], were the primary materials used in the construction of the masjid. The structure displays a compact rectangular plan, with a domed [[mihrab]] axis. Glazed tiles were also used in the decoration of the mihrab, one of which bears a dated inscription.\n\nPhotographs of the Fakr ad-Din mosque feature in drawings and images of central Mogadishu from the late 19th century onwards. The mosque can be identified amidst other buildings by its two cones, one round and the other hexagonal.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arba'a Rukun Mosque]]\n*[[Masjid al-Qiblatayn]]\n*[[Mosque of Islamic Solidarity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121104013318/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=7810 Masjid Fakhr al-Din]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070607173848/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.tcl?site_id=7810 ArchNet - Masjid Fakhr al-Din]\n\n{{Mosques in Somalia}}\n\n{{coord|2|02|01|N|45|20|09|E|region:SO_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Mosques in Somalia]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures completed in 1269]]\n[[Category:13th-century mosques]]\n\n\n{{Somalia-struct-stub}}\n{{Africa-mosque-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Abubakar Ibrahim Mohamed", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fakr_ad-Din_Mosque"}
