ournal|author=Tachau, Frank. |title=The Search for National Identity among the Turks|journal= Die Welt des Islams|series= New Series|volume= 8|issue=3 |date=1963| pp= 165\u2013176}}</ref><ref name=\"Cook\">{{cite journal |first=Steven A. |last=Cook |title=Recent History: The Rise of the Justice and Development Party |journal=U.S.-Turkey Relations: A New Partnership to|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations |year=2012 |page=52}}</ref><br />[[Cultural nationalism]]<ref name=\"Cook\"/><ref>{{cite journal |first=Fatma M\u00fcge |last=G\u00f6\u00e7ek |title=The Transformation of Turkey: Redefining State and Society from the Ottoman Empire to the Modern Era |publisher=I.B. Tauris |year=2011 |page=56}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Nathalie |last=Tocci |title=Turkey and the European Union |journal=The Routledge Handbook of Modern Turkey |publisher=Routledge |year=2012 |page=241}}</ref><br />[[Social conservatism]]<ref>{{cite journal|title=Turkey's Radical Right and the Kurdish Issue: The MHP's Reaction to the \"Democratic Opening\"|first=\u00d6d\u00fcl|last=Celep|year=2010|journal=[[Insight Turkey]]|volume=12|issue=2}}</ref><br />[[National conservatism]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Turkey and the European Union: Domestic Politics, Economic Integration and International Dynamics|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|page=127|first=Ali|last=Carkoglu}}</ref><br />[[Right-wing populism]]<ref name=\"Farnen\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Farnen|editor1-first=Russell F.|title=Nationalism, Ethnicity, and Identity: Cross National and Comparative Perspectives|date=2004|publisher=Transaction Secularism Publishers|isbn=9781412829366|page=252|quote=..the nationalist-fascist Turkish National Movement Party (MHP).}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Abadan-Unat|first1=Nermin|title=Turks in Europe: From Guest Worker to Transnational Citizen|date=2011|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=New York|isbn=9781845454258|page=19|quote=...the fascist Nationalist Movement Party...}}</ref><br />[[Euroscepticism]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Euroscepticism: Party Ideology Meets Strategy| url =https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233292008}}</ref>}}<br />[[Pan-Turkism]]<ref>{{cite news|title=MHP to start rallies against Kurdish terrorist movement on Dec 13|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/newsDetail.action;jsessionid=3Ghv60BSd63UASpRJxK9ZPhJ?newsId=194568&columnistId=0|accessdate=4 January 2015|work=Today's Zaman|date=4 December 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104161345/http://www.todayszaman.com/newsDetail.action;jsessionid=3Ghv60BSd63UASpRJxK9ZPhJ?newsId=194568&columnistId=0|archivedate=4 January 2015}}</ref><br />[[Turanism]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=S\u00f6yler|first1=Mehtap|title=The Turkish Deep State: State Consolidation, Civil-Military Relations and Democracy|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317668800|page=119|url=https://books.google.com.au/books/about/The_Turkish_Deep_State.html?id=CcKgBgAAQBAJ|language=en}}</ref>\n| seats1_title = [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Grand National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|49|600|#870000}}\n| seats2_title = [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|Metropolitan municipalities]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|30|#870000}}\n| seats3_title = [[List of municipalities in Turkey|District municipalities]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|233|1351|#870000}}\n| seats5_title = [[2014 Turkish local elections|Provincial councillors]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|188|1251|#870000}}\n| colours = {{Color box|#CC0000|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#FFFFFF|border=darkgray}} [[Red]], [[White]] (official)<br />{{Color box|#870000|border=darkgray}} [[Ruby red]] (customary)\n| slogan = ''\u00dclkenin Gelece\u011fine Oy Ver'' (\"Vote for the Country's Future\")\n| seats6_title = [[2014 Turkish local elections|Municipal Assemblies]]\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|2819|20498|#870000}}\n| flag = [[File:Flag of the Nationalist Movement Party.svg|200px|border|Flag of the Nationalist Movement Party]]\n| website = {{url|http://www.mhp.org.tr/|www.mhp.org.tr}}\n| country = Turkey\n}}\n\nThe '''Nationalist Movement Party''' (alternatively translated as '''Nationalist Action Party'''; {{lang-tr|Milliyet\u00e7i Hareket Partisi}}, '''MHP''') is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] [[Far-right politics|far-right]] \n[[Conservatism|ultraconservative]] political party that adheres to Turkish [[ultranationalism]] and [[Euroscepticism]].\n\nThe party was formed in 1969 by former colonel [[Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f]], who had become leader of the [[Republican Villagers Nation Party]] (CKMP) in 1965. The party mainly followed a [[Pan-Turkism|Pan-Turkist]] and nationalist political agenda throughout the latter half of the 20th century, but later moderated its views under the leadership of [[Devlet Bah\u00e7eli]], who took over after T\u00fcrke\u015f's death in 1997. The party's youth wing is the [[Grey Wolves (organization)|Gray Wolves]] (''Bozkurtlar'') organization, which is also known as the \"Nationalist Hearths\" (''\u00dclk\u00fc Ocaklar\u0131'').{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} T\u00fcrke\u015f, who is widely revered by Turkish nationalists as the founder of the idealist movement, is commonly referred to as \"Chieftain\" (''Ba\u015fbu\u011f'') by his supporters.\n\nAlparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f founded the party after criticizing the [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] (CHP) for moving too far away from the nationalist principles of their founder [[Mustafa Kemal Atat\u00fcrk]], claiming that he would not have founded the MHP had the CHP not deviated from Atat\u00fcrk's ideology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulkuocaklari.org.tr/biz-kimiz-saday-alisov.html|title=Biz Kimiz? \u2013 Ahmet \u015eefki Kuzulu - \u00dclk\u00fc Ocaklar\u0131 E\u011fitim ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Vakf\u0131}}</ref> Although T\u00fcrke\u015f failed to win any elections, the MHP won enough seats in the [[1973 Turkish general election|1973]] and [[1977 Turkish general election|1977 general election]] to take part in two coalition governments led by [[Justice Party (Turkey)|Justice Party]] (AP) leader [[S\u00fcleyman Demirel]]. T\u00fcrke\u015f served as the [[Deputy Prime Minister of Turkey]] between 1975 and 1977 in what was referred to as the [[39th government of Turkey|First Nationalist Front]] government and again between 1977 and 1978 in the [[41st government of Turkey|Second Nationalist Front]]. After T\u00fcrke\u015f's death and the [[1997 Nationalist Movement Party Extraordinary Congress|election]] of Devlet Bah\u00e7eli as his successor, the party moderated its views and adopted a more mainstream nationalist agenda. The party under Bah\u00e7eli's leadership won 18% of the vote and 129 seats in the [[1999 Turkish general election|1999 general election]], its best ever result, coming second only to the [[Democratic Left Party (Turkey)|Democratic Left Party]] (DSP). Bah\u00e7eli subsequently became Deputy Prime Minister after [[57th government of Turkey|entering a coalition]] with the DSP and the [[Motherland Party (Turkey)|Motherland Party]] (ANAP), though his calls for an early election resulted in the government's collapse in 2002. In the [[2002 Turkish general election|2002 general election]], the MHP fell below the 10% [[election threshold]] and lost all of its parliamentary representation after the newly formed [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]] (AKP) won a plurality.\n\nSince the [[2007 Turkish general election|2007 general election]], in which the MHP won back its parliamentary representation with 14.27% of the vote and 71 seats, the party has strongly opposed the [[Solution process|peace negotiations]] between the government and Kurdish separatist militants and has been fiercely critical of the governing AKP over government corruption and authoritarianism. Nevertheless, the MHP has often been referred to critics as the \"AKP's lifeline\", having either openly or covertly helped the AKP in situations such as the [[2007 Turkish presidential election|2007 presidential election]], repealing the headscarf ban and the [[Turkish Parliament Speaker election, June\u2013July 2015|June\u2013July 2015 parliamentary speaker elections]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://haber.sol.org.tr/turkiye/levent-gok-mhpnin-akpye-can-simidi-olduguna-herkes-tanik-oldu-124609|title=Levent G\u00f6k: MHP'nin, AKP'ye can simidi oldu\u011funa herkes tan\u0131k oldu|date=30 July 2015}}</ref> In the [[2011 Turkish general election|2011 general election]], the party's vote fell to 13% and won 53 seats, though increased to 16.3% and 80 seats in the [[June 2015 Turkish general election|June 2015 general election]]. Having consistently maintained third-party status in Parliament since 2007, the MHP halved its parliamentary representation to win 40 seats with 11.9% of the vote in the [[November 2015 Turkish general election|November 2015 general election]], becoming the fourth largest party in Parliament behind the [[Peoples' Democratic Party (Turkey)|Peoples' Democratic Party]] (HDP). The MHP supported a 'Yes' vote in the [[2017 Turkish constitutional referendum|2017 referendum]], and formed the [[People's Alliance (Turkey)|People's Alliance]] electoral pact with the AKP for the [[2019 Turkish general election|2018 Turkish general election]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Reuters]]|date=21 February 2018|title=Erdogan's AKP says to ally with nationalists for 2019 elections|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-election-regulation/erdogans-akp-says-to-ally-with-nationalists-for-2019-elections-idUSKCN1G52DP}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Before 1980===\nIn 1965, nationalist politician and ex-[[Colonel]] Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f, who had trained in the [[United States]] for [[North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]], founded the [[Operation Gladio#Turkey|Turkish Gladio]] [[Special Warfare Department]], gained control of the conservative rural [[Republican Villagers Nation Party]] ({{lang-tr|Cumhuriyet\u00e7i K\u00f6yl\u00fc Millet Partisi}}, CKMP). During an Extraordinary Great Congress held at [[Adana]] in Turkey on 8\u20139 February 1969, T\u00fcrke\u015f changed the name of the party to the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP).\n\nThe MHP embraced Turkish nationalism, and under the leadership of T\u00fcrke\u015f, militias connected to the party were responsible for [[assassination|assassinating]] numerous [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] intellectuals and academics, including some Kurds, during the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=United States and NATO inspired 'psychological warfare operations' against the 'Kurdish communist threat' in Turkey |author=[[Desmond Fernandes]] and Iskender Ozden |url=http://www.variant.randomstate.org/pdfs/issue12/Fernandes.pdf |journal=[[Variant (magazine)|Variant]] |date=Spring 2001 |volume=2 |issue=12 |pages=10\u201316 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305194604/http://www.variant.randomstate.org/pdfs/issue12/Fernandes.pdf |archivedate=March 5, 2009 }}</ref> The leader of the party's youth wing, known as the [[Grey Wolves (organization)|Grey Wolves]] after Turkic [[mythology]], claimed that they had an intelligence organization that was superior to the state's own.<ref>{{Cite book|first=M. Emin|last=De\u011fer|location=Ankara|year=1978|publisher=Kendi Yay\u0131n\u0131|title=CIA, Kontrgerilla ve T\u00fcrkiye|language=Turkish|quote=MHP lideri T\u00fcrke\u015f, \u00dclk\u00fc Ocaklar\u0131n\u0131 me\u015fru m\u00fcdafaa yapt\u0131\u011f\u0131n\u0131 s\u00f6yler. \u00dclk\u00fc Ocaklar\u0131 Genel Ba\u015fkan\u0131 da, 'bizim istihbarat \u00f6rg\u00fct\u00fcm\u00fcz devletin   \u00f6rg\u00fct\u00fcnden g\u00fc\u00e7l\u00fcd\u00fcr' demektedir.|page=119}} Quoted in {{Cite journal |url=http://kurtulusyolu.org/gazete/tam_goster.php?fid=273 |accessdate=2008-11-04 |title=Susurluk'ta b\u00fct\u00fcn yollar, devlete u\u011frayarak CIA'ya \u00e7\u0131kar |journal=Kurtulu\u015f Yolu |date=2008-09-19 |language=Turkish |volume=4 |issue=39 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519200925/http://kurtulusyolu.org/gazete/tam_goster.php?fid=273 |archivedate=2009-05-19 }}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, MHP had links to the ''Ayd\u0131nlar Oca\u011f\u0131'' (AO; \"Hearth of Intellectuals\"), a [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] [[think tank]] launched in 1970 by established university professors, which served as a connecting link between [[Secularism|secular]]-conservative, nationalist and Islamic rightists, promoting the ideology of Turkish-Islamic synthesis. AO's ideas, which have been compared to those of the [[France|French]] [[Nouvelle Droite]], had a determining influence on MHP's programmes and served to lend the far-right party a more legitimate, respectable appearance.<ref name=\"Arikan1999_122\">{{Cite book |first=E. Burak |last=Ar\u0131kan |title=The Programme of the Nationalist Action Party: An Iron Hand in a Velvet Glove? |work=Turkey Before and After Atat\u00fcrk |publisher=Frank Cass |year=1999 |pages=122\u2013125}}</ref>\n\nOn May 27, 1980, the party's deputy leader and former government minister [[G\u00fcn Sazak]] was assassinated by members of the [[Marxism\u2013Leninism|Marxist\u2013Leninist]] terrorist group [[Revolutionary People's Liberation Party\u2013Front|Revolutionary Left]] ({{lang-tr| Devrimci Sol}} or ''Dev Sol'') in front of his home.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/22371764.asp |newspaper=[[H\u00fcrriyet]] |title=M\u0130T'ten 1 May\u0131s ve G\u00fcn Sazak yan\u0131t\u0131 |date=2013-01-16 |language=Turkish |accessdate=2014-02-11 }}</ref>\n\nWhen the Turkish army [[1980 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat|seized power on September 12, 1980]], in a violent ''coup d'\u00e9tat'' led by General [[Kenan Evren]], the party was banned, along with all other active political parties at the time, and many of its leading members were imprisoned. Many party members joined the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal]] [[Anavatan Partisi]] or various [[Islamist]] parties. Party member (Ag\u00e2h Oktay G\u00fcner) noted that the party's ideology was in power while its members were in prison.\n\n===Re-establishment===\nThe party was reformed in 1983 under the name \"Conservative Party\" ({{lang-tr|Muhafazakar Parti}}). After 1985, however, the name was changed to the \"Nationalist Task Party\" ({{lang-tr|Milliyet\u00e7i \u00c7al\u0131\u015fma Partisi}}) then back again to its former name in 1992.<ref name=\"mhp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mhp.org.tr/mhp_tarihce.php |accessdate=June 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817200019/http://www.mhp.org.tr/mhp_tarihce.php |archivedate=August 17, 2010 }}{{Better source|date=September 2010}}</ref> In 1993, [[Muhsin Yaz\u0131c\u0131o\u011flu]] and five other deputies separated and founded the [[Great Union Party]], which is an Islamist party.<ref name=\"mhp\" />\n\n==Ideology==\nThe MHP's view represents the Nine-Light doctrine, based on Turkish nationalism shaped by [[Islam]]. The MHP used to be described as a neo-fascist party<ref name=\"Arikan1999_122\"/><ref>{{Cite book |first=Tim |last=Jacoby |title=Fascism, Civility and the Crisis of the Turkish State |work=Political Civility in the Middle East |publisher=Routledge |year=2012 |page=112}}</ref> linked to extremist and violent militias.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Colleen |last=Sullivan |title=Grey Wolves |work=The SAGE Encyclopedia of Terrorism |edition=Second |publisher=Sage |year=2011 |page=236}}</ref> Since the 1990s it has, under the leadership of Devlet Bah\u00e7eli, gradually moderated its programme, turning from [[ethnic nationalism|ethnic]] to [[cultural nationalism]] and conservatism and stressing the unitary nature of the Turkish state. Notably, it has moved from strict, [[Kemalism|Kemalist]]-style secularism to a more pro-Islamic stance, and has &ndash; at least in public statements &ndash; accepted the rules of [[parliamentary democracy]]. Some scholars{{who|date=June 2015}} doubt the sincerity and credibility of this turn and suspect the party of still pursuing a [[fascism|fascist]] agenda behind a more moderate and pro-democratic fa\u00e7ade. Nevertheless, MHP's mainstream overture has strongly increased its appeal to voters and it has grown to the country's third-strongest party,<ref>{{Cite book |first1=Peter |last1=Davies |first2=Paul |last2=Jackson |title=The Far Right in Europe: An Encyclopedia |publisher=Greenwood |year=2008 |page=358}}</ref> continuously represented in the National Assembly since 2007 with voter shares well above the 10% threshold.\n\n===Opposition to the HDP===\nDue to their ideological differences, the MHP is strongly opposed to any form of dialogue with the left-wing Kurdish nationalist Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP), which Devlet Bah\u00e7eli has often opposed by voting against in Parliament. A notable example was in the June\u2013July 2015 parliamentary speaker elections, where the MHP declared that they would not support any candidate and cast blank votes after the HDP announced support for the Republican People's Party (CHP) candidate [[Deniz Baykal]]. The MHP also ruled out any prospect of a coalition government that receives support from the HDP after the [[June 2015 Turkish general election|June 2015 general election]] resulted in a [[hung parliament]], even rejecting CHP leader [[Kemal K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7daro\u011flu|Kemal K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7daro\u011flu's]] offer of Bah\u00e7eli becoming Prime Minister in such a coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://t24.com.tr/haber/kilicdaroglundan-bahceliye-akpnin-koltuk-degnekcisi,301539|title=K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7daro\u011flu'ndan Bah\u00e7eli'ye: AKP'nin koltuk de\u011fnek\u00e7isi!}}</ref> MHP deputy leader [[Celal Adan]] claimed that 'even using our party's name in the same sentence as the HDP will be counted as cruelty by us.'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cihan.com.tr/tr/partimiz-ile-hdpnin-ayni-cumle-icinde-kullanilmasini-bile-zul-sayariz-1806290.htm|title='Partimiz ile HDP'nin ayn\u0131 c\u00fcmle i\u00e7inde kullan\u0131lmas\u0131n\u0131 bile zul sayar\u0131z'}}</ref>\n\nIn early September 2015, the MHP and the HDP both voted against the new [[2015 interim election government of Turkey|interim election government]] ministers from taking their oaths of office, causing speculation of whether the MHP was dropping their harsh stance against the HDP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/politika/chp-mhp-ve-hdp-ayni-oyu-verdi-tbmmde-yemin-krizi-cikti-1427432/|title=CHP, MHP ve HDP ayn\u0131 oyu verdi, TBMM'de yemin krizi \u00e7\u0131kt\u0131}}</ref> However, [[Semih Yal\u00e7\u0131n]] downplayed any notions of an alliance between the two parties, stating that \"a broken clock will still show the correct time once a day, the HDP can sometimes take a correct decision in Parliament. Showing this as a 'MHP-HDP coalition' is a deliberate diversion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yeniakit.com.tr/haber/mhpden-hdp-ile-ilgili-ittifak-aciklamasi-91744.html|title=MHP'den HDP ile ilgili 'ittifak' a\u00e7\u0131klamas\u0131}}</ref>\n\n==Economic policies==\n\nDuring the [[June 2015 Turkish general election]], the MHP announced a new economic manifesto. The MHP promised to improve the situation of Turkey\u2019s working poor by lifting taxes on diesel and fertiliser, raising the net minimum wage to $518, giving a $37 transportation subsidy to every minimum wage worker, and giving those who cannot afford a house an additional $92 per month in rental aid. The MHP said these policies would allow a minimum wage earner living in a big city to earn as much an extra $646 annually.\n\nThe MHP stated that their economic policies would create 700,000 jobs, increase the national income per person to $13.3K, and increase exports to $238 billion while keeping annual growth at 5.2 percent between 2016 and 2019.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn July 2015, amidst [[Xinjiang conflict#2015 anti-China protests in Turkey|a wave of protests]] against the [[Xinjiang conflict]], MHP-affiliated ''[[\u00dclk\u00fc Ocaklar\u0131|\u00dclk\u00fcc\u00fc]]'' attacked [[South Korea]]n tourists on Istanbul's [[Sultanahmet Square]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Koreans and Chinese 'both have slanted eyes,' Turkey's nationalist leader says over attacks on tourists |work=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/koreans-and-chinese-both-have-slanted-eyes-turkeys-nationalist-leader-says-over-attacks-on-tourists.aspx |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> In an interview to Turkish columnist [[Ahmet Hakan]], MHP leader Devlet Bah\u00e7eli played the attacks down,<ref>{{cite web |author=Ahmet Hakan |title=Koreans and Chinese 'both have slanted eyes,' Turkey's nationalist leader says over attacks on tourists |work=[[H\u00fcrriyet Daily News]] |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/koreans-and-chinese-both-have-slanted-eyes-turkeys-nationalist-leader-says-over-attacks-on-tourists.aspx |date=8 July 2015 |accessdate=24 November 2015|author-link=Ahmet Hakan }}</ref> stating that \"These are young kids. They may have been provoked. Plus, how are you going to differentiate between Korean and Chinese? They both have slanted eyes. Does it really matter?\"<ref name=Tremblay>{{cite web|author=Pinar Tremblay |title=Attacks on Chinese escalate in Turkey |work=[[Al Monitor]] |url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2015/07/turkey-china-random-violence-become-norm-in-lgbt.html |date=20 July 2015 |accessdate=24 November 2015}}</ref> Bahceli's remarks were widely considered racist, and together with a banner reading \"We crave Chinese blood\" at the \u00dclk\u00fcc\u00fc Istanbul headquarters, the affair caused an uproar in both Turkish and international media.<ref name=Tremblay />\n\n==Party leaders==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! #\n! Leader<br /><small>(Birth\u2013Death)</small>\n! Portrait\n! Constituency\n! Took Office\n! Left Office\n|-\n|style=\"background: #d50000\"| {{white|'''1'''}} || [[Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f|Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f]]<br /><small>(1917\u20131997)</small>\n| [[File:Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f'in portresi.jpg|75px]] || [[Ankara (electoral districts)|Ankara]] ([[1965 Turkish general election|1965]])<br />[[Adana (electoral district)|Adana]] ([[1969 Turkish general election|1969]], [[1973 Turkish general election|1973]], [[1977 Turkish general election|1977]])<br />[[Yozgat (electoral district)|Yozgat]] ([[1991 Turkish general election|1991]])\n| 8 February 1969 || 4 April 1997\n|-\n|style=\"background: #d50000\"| {{white|'''&ndash;'''}} || [[Muhittin \u00c7olak]] (acting) || || || 5 April 1997 || 6 July 1997\n|-\n|style=\"background: #d50000\"| {{white|'''2'''}} || [[Devlet Bah\u00e7eli]]<br /><small>(1948\u2013 )</small>\n| [[File:Devlet Bah\u00e7eli VOA 2015 (cropped).jpg|75px]] || <br />[[Osmaniye (electoral district)|Osmaniye]] ([[1999 Turkish general election|1999]], [[2007 Turkish general election|2007]], [[2011 Turkish general election|2011]], [[June 2015 Turkish general election|Jun]]/[[November 2015 Turkish general election|Nov 2015]])\n| 6 July 1997 || incumbent\n|-\n|}\n\n==present status==\nThe party is headed by Devlet Bah\u00e7eli and has 49<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secim.haberler.com/|title=SE\u00c7\u0130M SONU\u00c7LARI - 2015 genel se\u00e7im sonu\u00e7lar\u0131}}</ref> deputies, three of them women, in the [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|Grand National Assembly]]. The party has recently been putting a distance between itself and its history of ultranationalism, at occasion asking its members to keep away from \"ethnic politics\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhpizmir.org.tr/basindamhp/2007/2007ekim.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827084715/http://www.mhpizmir.org.tr/basindamhp/2007/2007ekim.htm |archivedate=2011-08-27 }}</ref>{{third-party-inline|date=June 2015}}\n\n\n==Election results==\n\n===General elections===\n[[File:\u015eile 4723.jpg|thumb|Flags of political parties before the Turkish municipal elections in [[\u015eile]], Istanbul, March 2009]]\n[[File:Devlet Bah\u00e7eli Ankara Miting 3.jpg|thumb|The MHP holding its electoral rally in [[Ankara]], May 2015]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey]]\n! text-align:center;\" | Election date\n! text-align:center;\" | Party leader\n! text-align:center;\" | Number of votes received\n! text-align:center;\" | Percentage of votes\n! text-align:center;\" | Number of deputies\n|-\n| [[1969 Turkish general election|1969]] || Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f || 274,225 || 3.02% || {{Composition bar|3|450|hex=#d50000}}\n|-\n| [[1973 Turkish general election|1973]] || Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f || 362,208 || 3.38% || {{Composition bar|3|450|hex=#d50000}}\n|-\n| [[1977 Turkish general election|1977]] ||  Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f || 951,544 || 6.42% || {{Composition bar|16|450|hex=#d50000}}\n|-\n| [[1995 Turkish general election|1995]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belgenet.net/ayrinti.php?yil_id%3D12 |accessdate=June 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723024542/http://www.belgenet.net/ayrinti.php?yil_id=12 |archivedate=July 23, 2011 }}</ref>  || Alparslan T\u00fcrke\u015f || 2,301,343 || 8.18% || {{Composition bar|0|550|hex=#d50000}}\n|-\n| [[1999 Turkish general election|1999]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belgenet.net/ayrinti.php?yil_id%3D13 |accessdate=June 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720033123/http://www.belgenet.net/ayrinti.php?yil_id=13 |archivedate=July 20, 2011 }}</ref>  || [[Devlet Bah\u00e7eli]] || 5,606,634 || 17.98% || {{Composition bar|129|550|hex=#d50000}}\n|-\n| [[2002 Turkish general election|2002]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belgenet.net/ayrinti.php?yil_id%3D14 |accessdate=June 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723024612/http://www.belgenet.net/ayrinti.php?yil_id=14 |archivedate=July 23, 2011 }}</ref>  || De