ame_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Badminton_at_the_1974_Asian_Games"}
{"title_page": "Boeing Orbital Flight Test", "text_new": "{{redirect-distinguish|Rosie the Rocketeer|Rosie the Rocketer}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name = Boe-OFT\n| image =Boeing Orbital Flight Test.jpg\n| image_caption = [[Atlas V]] lifts off carrying Starliner for OFT\n| mission_type = Test flight\n| operator = {{Hlist|[[NASA]]|[[Boeing]]}}\n| COSPAR_ID = \n| SATCAT = 44900\n| mission_duration = {{time interval|2019-12-20 11:36:43|2019-12-22 12:58:53|show=dhms|sep=,}}\n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed = 33<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lPzNHeX7OYM Boeing Starliner Orbital Flight Test Landing]</ref>\n| spacecraft = [[Boeing Starliner Spacecraft 3|''Calypso'']]<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Astro_Suni |number=1208780116630876160 |date=December 22, 2019 |title=Thanking two mission control personnel |last=Williams|first=Sunita}}</ref>\n| spacecraft_type = [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner|CST-100 Starliner]]\n| manufacturer = [[Boeing]]\n| launch_mass = {{convert|NNNN|abbr=on}}\n| landing_mass = {{convert|NNNN|abbr=on}}\n| launch_date = 20 December 2019 11:36:43 UTC<ref name=\"sfn-20191203\">{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/12/03/launch-of-starliner-test-flight-slips-to-dec-19/ |title=Launch of first Starliner orbital test flight slips to Dec. 19 |work=Spaceflight Now |date=3 December 2019 |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=SPFN>[https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/12/18/atlas-5-av-080-starliner-oft-mission-status-center/ Live coverage: Overnight countdown underway for Friday\u2019s Starliner launch]</ref>\n| launch_rocket = [[Atlas V]] N22 (AV-080)\n| launch_site = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| landing_date = 22 December 2019 12:58:53 UTC\n| landing_site = [[White Sands Missile Range]]\n| apsis = gee\n| orbit_epoch = \n| orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis = \n| orbit_apoapsis = \n| orbit_period = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\n| insignia = [[File:Boeing Orbital Flight Test.png|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n| insignia_alt = Boeing insignia, featuring the Starliner and a docking port above a wreath representing the Earth's horizon\n| programme = '''[[Commercial Crew Development]]'''\n| previous_mission = [[Boeing Pad Abort Test]]\n| next_mission = [[Dragon 2 In-Flight Abort Test]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Boeing Orbital Flight Test''' (also known as '''Boe-OFT''') was the first orbital mission of the [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner|CST-100 Starliner]] spacecraft, conducted by [[Boeing Defense, Space & Security|Boeing]] as part of [[NASA]]'s [[Commercial Crew Development|Commercial Crew Program]]. The mission was planned to be an eight-day test flight of the spacecraft, involving a rendezvous and docking with the [[International Space Station]] (ISS), and a landing in the western United States. The mission was successfully launched on 20 December 2019 at 11:36 UTC or 6:36 AM EST, however an issue with the spacecraft's [[mission elapsed time]] (MET) clock occurred 31 minutes into flight. This anomaly caused the spacecraft to burn into an incorrect orbit, preventing a rendezvous with the ISS. The mission was reduced to just two days, with the spacecraft successfully landing at [[White Sands Missile Range]] on 22 December. \n\nOn 6 April 2020, Boeing announced that they would redo the Orbital Flight Test to prove and meet all of the test objectives. NASA accepted the proposal from Boeing to do another uncrewed test flight. The redo flight is scheduled for October 2020. <ref>[https://twitter.com/BoeingSpace/status/1247279990242250753?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1247279990242250753&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.popularmechanics.com%2Fspace%2Frockets%2Fa32058019%2Fboeing-starliner-second-flight%2F]</ref>\n\n== Payload ==\n{{anchor|Rosie|Rosie the Rocketeer}}\nInstead of carrying astronauts, the flight carried an [[Crash test dummy|Anthropomorphic Test Device]] (ATD) wearing Boeing's [[Space suit#SpaceX suit|custom flight suit]]. The ATD is named Rosie (aka \"Rosie the Rocketeer\"<ref name=\"FloridaToday-20191121\"> {{cite news|author=Rachael Joy|url=https://www.floridatoday.com/story/tech/science/space/2019/11/21/boeing-names-test-dummy-fly-aboard-first-starliner-flight-after-iconic-rosie-riveter/4230233002/|title=Remember Rosie the Riveter? Meet Rosie the Rocketeer|date=21 November 2019|publisher=Florida Today}}  </ref>), as a homage to all the women who helped contribute to the Starliner Program.<ref name=\"Space-20191216\"> {{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/boeing-starliner-rosie-astronaut-test-dummy.html|title=Rosie, a Bandana-Clad Test Dummy, Will Be the First to Fly on Boeing's Starliner|author=Chelsea Gohd|date=16 December 2019|publisher=Space.com}} </ref> The capsule was weighted similarly to missions with astronauts onboard and carried approximately {{cvt|600|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of supplies and equipment including a plush toy of Snoopy and holiday presents for the [[Expedition 61]] crew members. Due to the inability to dock with the ISS, this cargo was never delivered.\n\n== Mission ==\nThe first [[Atlas V]] N22, designated AV-080, launched the CST-100 Starliner spacecraft on an uncrewed test flight to the [[International Space Station]]. The capsule was intended to dock with the space station, then return to Earth to land in the Western United States after an orbital [[shakedown cruise]] ahead of [[Boeing Crewed Flight Test]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOFT is the first flight of an [[Atlas V]] without a payload fairing and its first flight with a [[Centaur (rocket stage)|dual-engine Centaur]] upper stage. The dual-engine Centaur utilizes two [[RL10|RL10s]] and is required for Starliner flights in order to provide a launch trajectory that allows for a safe abort at any point in the mission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/11/starliner-arrives-launch-pad-major-milestone/|title=Starliner arrives at launch pad in major pre-flight milestone|date=2019-11-21|website=NASASpaceFlight.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nThe mission launched successfully on 20 December 2019 at 6:36:43{{nbsp}}am EST,{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} but thirty-one minutes after launch the mission elapsed timer (MET) clock made an error and forced an abort to the ISS. During a later press conference, it was revealed that MET was offset by 11 hours.  When it became obvious that the maneuver did not happen, NASA and Boeing tried sending commands to get Starliner back on track, but the position of the spacecraft switching communications between two [[TDRS]] satellites made the maneuver misfire inevitable.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} This resulted in an abort in ISS rendezvous. The decision was made by NASA and Boeing since the spacecraft burned too much fuel to reach the ISS even after Mission Control fixed the MET clock issue. NASA and Boeing officials placed the spacecraft in a different orbit and the entire flight plan had to be redone and the mission was reduced from eight days to three flight days.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nBy 7:40{{nbsp}}am EST, the Starliner was in a \"stable orbit\", though orbital insertion was not nominal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boeing, ULA launches of Starliner, suffers orbital insertion issue |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/12/boeing-ula-momentous-starliner-uncrewed-test-flight/ |work=NASASpaceFlight.com |date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> It was later confirmed that Starliner had placed itself into a 187 x 222 km orbit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cgbassa/status/1208019783242911746|title=There's a second set of orbital elements released now. 187 x 222 km, with epoch at 13:20UTC.|last=Bassa|first=Cees|date=2019-12-20|website=@cgbassa|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref> \n\nBy 8:55{{nbsp}}am EST, mission control had realized that docking with the ISS was precluded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JimBridenstine/status/1208021843388633090|title=Because #Starliner believed it was in an orbital insertion burn (or that the burn was complete), the dead bands were reduced and the spacecraft burned more fuel than anticipated to maintain precise control. This precluded @Space_Station rendezvous.|last=Bridenstine|first=Jim|date=2019-12-20|website=@JimBridenstine|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n[[File:Calypso Starliner capsule postflight.jpg|thumb|\"Calypso\" in processing after returning to Earth]]\nOn 22 December, Starliner was cleared to reenter the Earth's atmosphere. After deorbiting, Starliner reentered the Earth's atmosphere before successfully deploying all sets of parachutes. Starliner deployed airbags and successfully touched-down at [[White Sands Missile Range]] at 7:58 AM ET.  Though the ISS rendezvous that was planned for the OFT did not happen, [[Jim Chilton]], vice president for Boeing\u2019s space and launch division, estimated that Starliner has achieved over 60% of the flight objectives, and this could reach over 85% once all the data from the spacecraft is retrieved and analyzed.<ref>https://spacenews.com/starliner-lands-in-new-mexico/</ref>\n\nThe spacecraft will later be reused on mission [[USCV-2]]. Its commander, [[Sunita Williams]], informally dubbed the spacecraft \u201cCalypso\u201d after the [[RV Calypso|famed oceanographic research ship]] and its eponymous John Denver song.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Astro_Suni |number=1208780116630876160 |date=December 22, 2019 |title=Thanking two mission control personnel |last=Williams|first=Sunita}}</ref>\n\n== Anomalies ==\nAn issue with the spacecraft's [[mission elapsed time]] (MET) clock occurred 31 minutes into flight. This anomaly caused the spacecraft to burn into an incorrect orbit, preventing a rendezvous with the ISS. The mission was reduced to just two days, with the spacecraft successfully landing at [[White Sands Missile Range]] on 22 December. After the mission it was revealed that another critical software bug was found in flight, which could have resulted in the [[service module]] bumping back into Starliner after separation. If this had occurred, it may have damaged Starliner and prevented a safe landing. Additionally it was determined that had the first anomaly not occurred, the second would not have been detected. While the mission completed some test objectives, NASA and Boeing are investigating the two anomalies to determine if another uncrewed test flight is needed before Starliner can launch passengers.\n\nOn 7 February 2020, NASA shared their preliminary findings about the Boeing OFT mission and discovered software problems with the Mission Elapsed Timer (MET), which incorrectly polled time from the Atlas V booster nearly 11 hours prior to launch. Another software issue occurred within the Service Module (SM) Disposal Sequence, which incorrectly translated the SM disposal sequence into the SM Integrated Propulsion Controller (IPC). This could have made the service module crash into the capsule after separation, potentially leading to a catastrophic failure of the capsule. In addition an Intermittent Space-to-Ground (S/G) forward link issue, which impeded the Flight Control team's ability to command and control the vehicle, was found. The current investigation is expected to last until end of February, in addition a full-scale safety review is planned that will likely take months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/07/tech/boeing-starliner-software-commercial-crew-ssn/index.html|title=Boeing's Starliner spacecraft, built to carry astronauts, faces new safety concerns|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/boeings-starliner-problems-may-be-worse-than-we-thought/|title=Boeing\u2019s Starliner problems may be worse than we thought|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]]\n*[[Crew Dragon Demo-1]], SpaceX's first (uncrewed) orbital mission for a capsule intended to carry crew.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.boeing.com/space/starliner/ Official Webpage of the CST-100 Starliner] \n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=21X5lGlDOfg NASA Live: Official Stream of NASA TV]\n\n{{Starliner spaceflights}}\n{{Unmanned ISS flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Boeing CST-100 Starliner]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect-distinguish|Rosie the Rocketeer|Rosie the Rocketer}}\n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name = Boe-OFT\n| image =Boeing Orbital Flight Test.jpg\n| image_caption = [[Atlas V]] lifts off carrying Starliner for OFT\n| mission_type = Test flight\n| operator = {{Hlist|[[NASA]]|[[Boeing]]}}\n| COSPAR_ID = \n| SATCAT = 44900\n| mission_duration = {{time interval|2019-12-20 11:36:43|2019-12-22 12:58:53|show=dhms|sep=,}}\n| distance_travelled = \n| orbits_completed = 33<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lPzNHeX7OYM Boeing Starliner Orbital Flight Test Landing]</ref>\n| spacecraft = ''Calypso''<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Astro_Suni |number=1208780116630876160 |date=December 22, 2019 |title=Thanking two mission control personnel |last=Williams|first=Sunita}}</ref>\n| spacecraft_type = [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner|CST-100 Starliner]]\n| manufacturer = [[Boeing]]\n| launch_mass = {{convert|NNNN|abbr=on}}\n| landing_mass = {{convert|NNNN|abbr=on}}\n| launch_date = 20 December 2019 11:36:43 UTC<ref name=\"sfn-20191203\">{{cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |url=https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/12/03/launch-of-starliner-test-flight-slips-to-dec-19/ |title=Launch of first Starliner orbital test flight slips to Dec. 19 |work=Spaceflight Now |date=3 December 2019 |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=SPFN>[https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/12/18/atlas-5-av-080-starliner-oft-mission-status-center/ Live coverage: Overnight countdown underway for Friday\u2019s Starliner launch]</ref>\n| launch_rocket = [[Atlas V]] N22 (AV-080)\n| launch_site = [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]] [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 41|SLC-41]]\n| landing_date = 22 December 2019 12:58:53 UTC\n| landing_site = [[White Sands Missile Range]]\n| apsis = gee\n| orbit_epoch = \n| orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis = \n| orbit_apoapsis = \n| orbit_period = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\n| insignia = [[File:Boeing Orbital Flight Test.png|frameless|upright=0.4]]\n| insignia_alt = Boeing insignia, featuring the Starliner and a docking port above a wreath representing the Earth's horizon\n| programme = '''[[Commercial Crew Development]]'''\n| previous_mission = [[Boeing Pad Abort Test]]\n| next_mission = [[Dragon 2 In-Flight Abort Test]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Boeing Orbital Flight Test''' (also known as '''Boe-OFT''') was the first orbital mission of the [[Boeing CST-100 Starliner|CST-100 Starliner]] spacecraft, conducted by [[Boeing Defense, Space & Security|Boeing]] as part of [[NASA]]'s [[Commercial Crew Development|Commercial Crew Program]]. The mission was planned to be an eight-day test flight of the spacecraft, involving a rendezvous and docking with the [[International Space Station]] (ISS), and a landing in the western United States. The mission was successfully launched on 20 December 2019 at 11:36 UTC or 6:36 AM EST, however an issue with the spacecraft's [[mission elapsed time]] (MET) clock occurred 31 minutes into flight. This anomaly caused the spacecraft to burn into an incorrect orbit, preventing a rendezvous with the ISS. The mission was reduced to just two days, with the spacecraft successfully landing at [[White Sands Missile Range]] on 22 December. \n\nOn 6 April 2020, Boeing announced that they would redo the Orbital Flight Test to prove and meet all of the test objectives. NASA accepted the proposal from Boeing to do another uncrewed test flight. The redo flight is scheduled for October 2020. <ref>[https://twitter.com/BoeingSpace/status/1247279990242250753?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1247279990242250753&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.popularmechanics.com%2Fspace%2Frockets%2Fa32058019%2Fboeing-starliner-second-flight%2F]</ref>\n\n== Payload ==\n{{anchor|Rosie|Rosie the Rocketeer}}\nInstead of carrying astronauts, the flight carried an [[Crash test dummy|Anthropomorphic Test Device]] (ATD) wearing Boeing's [[Space suit#SpaceX suit|custom flight suit]]. The ATD is named Rosie (aka \"Rosie the Rocketeer\"<ref name=\"FloridaToday-20191121\"> {{cite news|author=Rachael Joy|url=https://www.floridatoday.com/story/tech/science/space/2019/11/21/boeing-names-test-dummy-fly-aboard-first-starliner-flight-after-iconic-rosie-riveter/4230233002/|title=Remember Rosie the Riveter? Meet Rosie the Rocketeer|date=21 November 2019|publisher=Florida Today}}  </ref>), as a homage to all the women who helped contribute to the Starliner Program.<ref name=\"Space-20191216\"> {{cite web|url=https://www.space.com/boeing-starliner-rosie-astronaut-test-dummy.html|title=Rosie, a Bandana-Clad Test Dummy, Will Be the First to Fly on Boeing's Starliner|author=Chelsea Gohd|date=16 December 2019|publisher=Space.com}} </ref> The capsule was weighted similarly to missions with astronauts onboard and carried approximately {{cvt|600|lb|kg|abbr=on}} of supplies and equipment including a plush toy of Snoopy and holiday presents for the [[Expedition 61]] crew members. Due to the inability to dock with the ISS, this cargo was never delivered.\n\n== Mission ==\nThe first [[Atlas V]] N22, designated AV-080, launched the CST-100 Starliner spacecraft on an uncrewed test flight to the [[International Space Station]]. The capsule was intended to dock with the space station, then return to Earth to land in the Western United States after an orbital [[shakedown cruise]] ahead of [[Boeing Crewed Flight Test]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOFT is the first flight of an [[Atlas V]] without a payload fairing and its first flight with a [[Centaur (rocket stage)|dual-engine Centaur]] upper stage. The dual-engine Centaur utilizes two [[RL10|RL10s]] and is required for Starliner flights in order to provide a launch trajectory that allows for a safe abort at any point in the mission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/11/starliner-arrives-launch-pad-major-milestone/|title=Starliner arrives at launch pad in major pre-flight milestone|date=2019-11-21|website=NASASpaceFlight.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>\n\nThe mission launched successfully on 20 December 2019 at 6:36:43{{nbsp}}am EST,{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} but thirty-one minutes after launch the mission elapsed timer (MET) clock made an error and forced an abort to the ISS. During a later press conference, it was revealed that MET was offset by 11 hours.  When it became obvious that the maneuver did not happen, NASA and Boeing tried sending commands to get Starliner back on track, but the position of the spacecraft switching communications between two [[TDRS]] satellites made the maneuver misfire inevitable.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} This resulted in an abort in ISS rendezvous. The decision was made by NASA and Boeing since the spacecraft burned too much fuel to reach the ISS even after Mission Control fixed the MET clock issue. NASA and Boeing officials placed the spacecraft in a different orbit and the entire flight plan had to be redone and the mission was reduced from eight days to three flight days.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nBy 7:40{{nbsp}}am EST, the Starliner was in a \"stable orbit\", though orbital insertion was not nominal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boeing, ULA launches of Starliner, suffers orbital insertion issue |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/12/boeing-ula-momentous-starliner-uncrewed-test-flight/ |work=NASASpaceFlight.com |date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> It was later confirmed that Starliner had placed itself into a 187 x 222 km orbit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cgbassa/status/1208019783242911746|title=There's a second set of orbital elements released now. 187 x 222 km, with epoch at 13:20UTC.|last=Bassa|first=Cees|date=2019-12-20|website=@cgbassa|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref> \n\nBy 8:55{{nbsp}}am EST, mission control had realized that docking with the ISS was precluded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JimBridenstine/status/1208021843388633090|title=Because #Starliner believed it was in an orbital insertion burn (or that the burn was complete), the dead bands were reduced and the spacecraft burned more fuel than anticipated to maintain precise control. This precluded @Space_Station rendezvous.|last=Bridenstine|first=Jim|date=2019-12-20|website=@JimBridenstine|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n[[File:Calypso Starliner capsule postflight.jpg|thumb|\"Calypso\" in processing after returning to Earth]]\nOn 22 December, Starliner was cleared to reenter the Earth's atmosphere. After deorbiting, Starliner reentered the Earth's atmosphere before successfully deploying all sets of parachutes. Starliner deployed airbags and successfully touched-down at [[White Sands Missile Range]] at 7:58 AM ET.  Though the ISS rendezvous that was planned for the OFT did not happen, [[Jim Chilton]], vice president for Boeing\u2019s space and launch division, estimated that Starliner has achieved over 60% of the flight objectives, and this could reach over 85% once all the data from the spacecraft is retrieved and analyzed.<ref>https://spacenews.com/starliner-lands-in-new-mexico/</ref>\n\nThe spacecraft will later be reused on mission [[USCV-2]]. Its commander, [[Sunita Williams]], informally dubbed the spacecraft \u201cCalypso\u201d after the [[RV Calypso|famed oceanographic research ship]] and its eponymous John Denver song.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Astro_Suni |number=1208780116630876160 |date=December 22, 2019 |title=Thanking two mission control personnel |last=Williams|first=Sunita}}</ref>\n\n== Anomalies ==\nAn issue with the spacecraft's [[mission elapsed time]] (MET) clock occurred 31 minutes into flight. This anomaly caused the spacecraft to burn into an incorrect orbit, preventing a rendezvous with the ISS. The mission was reduced to just two days, with the spacecraft successfully landing at [[White Sands Missile Range]] on 22 December. After the mission it was revealed that another critical software bug was found in flight, which could have resulted in the [[service module]] bumping back into Starliner after separation. If this had occurred, it may have damaged Starliner and prevented a safe landing. Additionally it was determined that had the first anomaly not occurred, the second would not have been detected. While the mission completed some test objectives, NASA and Boeing are investigating the two anomalies to determine if another uncrewed test flight is needed before Starliner can launch passengers.\n\nOn 7 February 2020, NASA shared their preliminary findings about the Boeing OFT mission and discovered software problems with the Mission Elapsed Timer (MET), which incorrectly polled time from the Atlas V booster nearly 11 hours prior to launch. Another software issue occurred within the Service Module (SM) Disposal Sequence, which incorrectly translated the SM disposal sequence into the SM Integrated Propulsion Controller (IPC). This could have made the service module crash into the capsule after separation, potentially leading to a catastrophic failure of the capsule. In addition an Intermittent Space-to-Ground (S/G) forward link issue, which impeded the Flight Control team's ability to command and control the vehicle, was found. The current investigation is expected to last until end of February, in addition a full-scale safety review is planned that will likely take months.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/07/tech/boeing-starliner-software-commercial-crew-ssn/index.html|title=Boeing's Starliner spacecraft, built to carry astronauts, faces new safety concerns|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/02/boeings-starliner-problems-may-be-worse-than-we-thought/|title=Boeing\u2019s Starliner problems may be worse than we thought|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Dragon 2|Crew Dragon]]\n*[[Crew Dragon Demo-1]], SpaceX's first (uncrewed) orbital mission for a capsule intended to carry crew.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.boeing.com/space/starliner/ Official Webpage of the CST-100 Starliner] \n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=21X5lGlDOfg NASA Live: Official Stream of NASA TV]\n\n{{Starliner spaceflights}}\n{{Unmanned ISS flights}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Boeing CST-100 Starliner]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched in 2019]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft which reentered in 2019]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Toby6250", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_Orbital_Flight_Test"}
